# Resume Engine

## Product DNA

**The branded resume is the product.** If we cannot deliver the best resume in our master format, the tool has no reason to exist. Every export path must match `master-resume-template.tex` — no alternate layouts, no stale preview HTML, no generic PDF generators.

## Single pipeline

```
Tailored Job + ParsedResume + ResumeRules
        ↓
resolveMasterResumePlaceholders()  →  master-resume-template.tex
        ↓
MasterResumePreviewModel (plain text view of same data)
        ↓
.tex | PDF | DOCX | Print Preview | assist-apply upload
```

- **Canonical layout:** `src/shared/master-resume-template.tex` (9pt extarticle, 0.35in margins). Do not alter section spacing macros at assembly time.
- **Placeholder map:** `master-resume-latex.ts` — every `[PLACEHOLDER]` maps to profile/job fields.
- **Exports:** `export-master.ts` — PDF/DOCX mirror template section order and density.
- **Preview:** `ResumePrintPreview` + `resume-preview-model.ts` — same model, never hand-built HTML.

## Rules

- Respect page budget and fit-band rules in `format-rules.ts` and `fit-bands.ts`.
- LaTeX hygiene: escape `%` as `\%`, spell out `and` instead of `&`.
- Experience bullets: prioritize quantified metrics (%, $, latency/cost) grounded in profile — never invented.
- Platform upload format (`platform-format.ts`) chooses PDF vs DOCX; content is always master-format.
- Types: `resume-engine/types.ts`, `resume-types.ts`, `resume-preview-model.ts`.
